<TITLE> Grenade kills policeman at Rwanda genocide museum </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KIGALI, April 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A grenade thrown by an unknown attacker killed a policeman guarding Rwanda's genocide museum on Friday, in a rare attack in the central African nation still mourning the 1994 ethnic slaughter, police said. "A man walked to the museum and threw a grenade at the policemen on guard. It killed one of them instantly," police spokesman Marcel Higiro said. Another policeman was seriously injured and has been hospitalised, he said. "It must be one of those extremist fellows still harbouring the genocide ideology," Higiro said. Rwanda is in the fifth day of an official week of mourning that follows the 14th anniversary of the start of 100 days in which Hutu extremists slaughtered 800,000 ethnic Tutsis and moderate Hutus. Some Hutus complain that the mourning period, during which all bars and other recreational facilities are shut down, enforces a perception of collective guilt against their ethnic gro
